<subSubSection box="[199,1008,943,969]" pageId="10" pageNumber="391" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,654,1113]" box="[199,1008,943,969]" pageId="10" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,943,969]" pageId="10" pageNumber="391">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for its relatively short aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="391" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,654,1113]" pageId="10" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,979,1005]" pageId="10" pageNumber="391">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[606,757,979,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hecaloidella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipenis">
<emphasis box="[606,757,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="391">H. longipenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and from the same locality. It can be distinguished from this and other similar species by its relatively short aedeagal shaft. A series of females with the same data (various dates) similar to this and 
<taxonomicName box="[367,520,1051,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hecaloidella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="391" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipenis">
<emphasis box="[367,520,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="391">H. longipenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been seen (BMNH), which could be either species; all have the pregenital sternite triangularly produced medially.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
